 🌐 APIs & Application Fundamentals (Week 3)

APIs (Application Programming Interfaces) allow different software applications to communicate with each other. APIs are widely used in web applications, mobile applications, cloud services, and enterprise software.

1. What is an API?

API (Application Programming Interface) is a set of rules and protocols that allows one application to communicate with another application.

Instead of accessing the database directly, the client sends a request to the API. The API processes the request, communicates with the backend application and database, and returns the response to the client.

Simple Definition

An API is a bridge that allows two applications to exchange data securely.

Real-World Example

Imagine ordering food using a food delivery app.

Customer → Places an order using the mobile app.
Waiter (API) → Takes the order to the kitchen.
Kitchen (Backend Application) → Prepares the food.
Store Room (Database) → Stores ingredients and order details.

The customer never enters the kitchen directly. Similarly, an application never accesses the database directly—it uses an API.

2. API Architecture

The communication flow is:

Client
   │
   ▼
API
   │
   ▼
Application (Backend)
   │
   ▼
Database
Step-by-Step Explanation
Step 1: Client

The client is the application used by the user.

Examples:

Mobile App
Website
Desktop Application

The client sends an HTTP request to the API.

Example:

User clicks "View Profile"
Step 2: API

The API receives the request.

Responsibilities:

Validate request
Authenticate user
Route request
Send request to backend service
Step 3: Backend Application

The backend contains business logic.

Responsibilities:

Process user request
Perform calculations
Fetch or update data
Communicate with database
Step 4: Database

The database stores information permanently.

Examples:

User accounts
Orders
Products
Employee records

The backend retrieves or updates data in the database and returns the result through the API.

3. Example Flow

Suppose a user opens a banking app to check their account balance.

Mobile App
      │
      ▼
API Gateway
      │
      ▼
Backend Service
      │
      ▼
Database
Complete Flow
User opens banking app.
Mobile app sends request to API.
API validates user.
API forwards request to backend.
Backend queries database.
Database returns balance.
Backend sends response to API.
API returns response to mobile app.
Balance is displayed to the user.
4. REST APIs

REST (Representational State Transfer) is the most commonly used architecture for designing web APIs.

REST APIs communicate using the HTTP protocol.

Characteristics
Stateless
Client-server architecture
Uses HTTP methods
Easy to use
Supports JSON and XML

Most modern applications use JSON for sending and receiving data.

5. HTTP Methods in REST APIs
GET

Used to retrieve data.

Example
GET /users

Response:

[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "name": "John"
  }
]
Real-world Example

Opening your profile page.

The application retrieves your information from the server.

POST

Used to create new data.

Example
POST /users

Request:

{
  "name": "Raj",
  "age": 24
}
Real-world Example

Creating a new account.

PUT

Used to replace an existing resource completely.

Example
PUT /users/1

Request:

{
  "name": "Raj Kumar",
  "age": 25
}

All fields are updated.

Real-world Example

Updating your complete profile.

PATCH

Used to update only specific fields.

Example
PATCH /users/1

Request:

{
  "age": 25
}

Only the age is updated.

Real-world Example

Changing only your phone number or email address.

DELETE

Used to delete data.

Example
DELETE /users/1

Deletes the user from the database.

Real-world Example

Deleting a social media account.

6. Difference Between PUT and PATCH
PUT	PATCH
Updates the entire resource	Updates only specified fields
Replaces all existing data	Modifies selected data
Larger request payload	Smaller request payload

Example:

Current user:

{
  "name": "Raj",
  "age": 24,
  "city": "Hyderabad"
}

PUT

{
  "name": "Raj Kumar",
  "age": 25,
  "city": "Hyderabad"
}

Entire resource is replaced.

PATCH

{
  "age": 25
}

Only the age changes.

7. HTTP Status Codes (Common Interview Topic)
Status Code	Meaning
200 OK	Request successful
201 Created	Resource created successfully
204 No Content	Request successful, no data returned
400 Bad Request	Invalid request from client
401 Unauthorized	Authentication required
403 Forbidden	Access denied
404 Not Found	Resource not found
500 Internal Server Error	Server-side error
8. Advantages of APIs
Enables communication between applications.
Improves software integration.
Allows secure access to backend services.
Supports automation.
Promotes code reusability.
Scalable and easy to maintain.

